Incident.Summary: Single vehicle collision, vehicle left the roadway. The driver was arrested for DUI/DWI. The driver was released to the care of medical staff.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
In-car camera operational, T-5. This incident was captured on a BWC.

Defendant: Francisco Rogelio Quezada
Soundex #/State: 16572935/TX
Date of Birth: 08/01/1978
Date of Arrest: 10/22/2023
Time of Arrest: 0100 hours
DUI # 23-110
 
OFFICER EXPERIENCE:
 
     I, TFC A. Piscopo-Bann #6748, am a sworn police officer, currently assigned to uniformed patrol with the Maryland State Police Leonardtown Barrack, located at 23200 Leonard Hall Drive, Leonardtown, MD 20650. I have approximately 7 years of law enforcement training and experience in impaired driver detection and enforcement and Controlled Dangerous Substance (CDS) investigations, while conducting uniformed patrol. I received training in the laws pertaining to Constitutional Law, including, but not limited to, the laws pertaining to Search and Seizure. Through all of this training and experience, I am familiar with different variations of the use, packaging, and distribution of Controlled Dangerous Substances. I am certified by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) in administering Standardized Field Sobriety Tests (SFSTs), Standardized Field Sobriety Instructor, Advance Roadside Impaired Driver Enforcement (ARIDE), and as a former Drug Recognition Expert (DRE). I have administered SFSTs on numerous occasions, which has resulted in over 80 arrests related to driving under the influence of alcohol, drugs, or a combination of drugs and alcohol. I have testified in cases before the District and Circuit Courts of St. Mary's County, Maryland, leading to the conviction of the defendants. I know from my training and experience that there are three phases in impaired driving detection and not every incident will have all three phases present. An arrest decision is made based on the evidence gathered as a totality of the circumstances to establish probable cause that the driver is impaired and unable to safely operate a vehicle.

NARRATIVE
 
    On October 22, 2021 at approximately 0037 hours, I was on duty operating my unmarked Maryland State Police patrol vehicle, T-5, when I responded to a single vehicle, motorcycle collision, with reported injuries, located in the area of 23788 Mervell Dean Road, Hollywood, MD 20636. I arrived on scene at approximately 0040 hours and observed the white and black motorcycle, laying on its side, approximately 20 feet off the roadway, on the southbound side or Mervell Dean Road, north of Ruth’s Way, in the ditch. I observed the driver of the motorcycle laying on his back approximately 25 feet in front of the motorcycle.
    
     I made contact with the driver, Francisco Rogelio Quezada (H/M 08/01/1978) who was later identified by his Texas driver’s license. While speaking with Mr. Quezada I observed blood on his face and hands from blunt force, with signs of a concussion. The helmet of Mr. Quezada was removed prior to my arrival.
   
     Mr. Quezada appeared to be dazed and confused. Mr. Quezada did not remember riding his motorcycle and did not know where he currently was. While speaking with Mr. Quezada, I detected a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath and person. Mr. Quezada’s speech was thick and slurred.
    
     The white and black motorcycle was later identified as a Harley Davidson FXRS, with California registration “22Y2350.” It should be noted, I observed the white and black Harley Davidson, leaving the area of Toots Bar, moments prior the call for service was being dispatched, while I was on a traffic stop. Toots Bar is a known establishment for serving alcoholic beverages.

     I made contact with the caller, Floyd Francis Ashley (W/M, 12/16/1969), who advised he saw the white and black Harley Davidson traveling southbound on Mervell Dean Road. Mr. Ashley advised he did not see the motorcycle leave the roadway, but did see it tumbling in the ditch. Mr. Ashley advised he turned around, made contact with the rider, and called 9-1-1. Mr. Ashley did not render any medical assistance to Mr. Quezada.
    Hollywood Rescue Squad arrived on scene and began to treat Mr. Quezada for his injuries. Once again, Mr. Quezada would not answer any of my questions due to no recollection of where he was and what he was doing. Additionally, no standardized field sobriety tests were completed due to Mr. Quezada’s injuries.

PRELIMINARY BREATH TEST (PBT) – This is a voluntary breath test that is administered to obtain an indication of Mr. Quezada's alcohol concentration. My PBT (serial #70008053) is tested monthly for accuracy, and it was found to be working properly.
Mr. Quezada was offered the PBT, and he consented to a preliminary breath test. BrAC was a .12.

ARREST

     Based on the following observations, I had reason to believe Mr. Quezada was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol:
* Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage on his breath 
* Thick, slurred speak
* Driving vehicle in an unsafe manner
* Failure to control vehicle to avoid a collision
* Failure to maintain lane of travel.

    For purposes of this report, I placed Mr. Quezada under arrest for DUI at approximately 0100 hours. Mr. Quezada was never placed in handcuffs due to his injuries.

    Mr. Quezada was transported to the University of Maryland Capital Region Medical Center via helicopter for treatment at approximately 0134 hours. I arrived at the hospital at approximately 0234 hours. I advised Mr. Quezada of his charges while at the hospital. While speaking with Mr. Quezada at the hospital, I continued to detect the odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath. Additionally, I noted his speech was slurred.

    Mr. Quezada was read the DR-15, Advice of Rights, in English while at the hospital. Mr. Quezada refused to take the blood test at approximately 0248 hours.

INTOXIMETER RESULT:
***REFUSED***
 
     Mr. Quezada was charged with TA 21-902(a1i) Driving Vehicle While Under the Influence of Alcohol (2NX0RJP), TA 21-902 (b1i) Driving Vehicle While Impaired by Alcohol (2NY0RJP), TA 21-901.1(b) Negligent Driving Vehicle In Careless and Imprudent Manner Endangering Property, Life and Person (2NZ0RJP), TA 21-901.1(a) Reckless Driving Vehicle in Wanton and Willful Disregard for Safety of Persons and Property (2P00RJP), and TA 21-801(b) Failure to Control Vehicle Speed on Highway to Avoid Collision (2P10RJP). Mr. Quezada received copies of all appropriate charging documents. I continued to detect the odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from Mr. Quezada’s breath while speaking with him at the hospital. Mr. Quezada was released to the care of the hospital.

     All events occurred in St. Mary's County, Maryland.

     Case closed by arrest.
